{"title_page": "James Barroll Ricaud", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = James Barroll Ricaud\n| image       = JamesBarrollRicaud.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = James Barroll Ricaud (1859)\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1808|02|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore, Maryland]], US\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1866|01|24|1808|02|11}}\n| death_place = [[Chestertown, Maryland]], US\n| death_cause =\n| resting_place =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| residence   = \n| nationality = American\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  = Politician\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| term        =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| party       =\n| boards      =\n| religion    =\n| spouse      =\n| partner     =\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes   =\n}}\n[[File:J B Ricaud.jpg|thumb|Title page from Abstract of Infantry Tactics including exercises and maneuvers of light infantry and riflemen for the use of the militia of the United States Published by the Department of War Under the authority of an Act of Congress of the 2D of March, 1829. This first edition was signed by James B. Ricaud and given to George Vickers who would later be a US Senator from Maryland. In the private collection of H. Blair Howell]]\n'''James Barroll Ricaud''' (February 11, 1808 &ndash; January 24, 1866) was an American politician.<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=R000192 Bioguide.congress.gov]</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], Ricaud attended the common schools and graduated from [[Washington College]] of [[Chestertown, Maryland]], in 1828.  He studied law, was admitted to the bar in 1829, and commenced practice in Chestertown.  He served as a member of the [[Maryland House of Delegates]] in 1834, served in the [[Maryland State Senate]] from 1836 to 1844, and served as [[presidential elector]] on the Whig tickets in 1840 and 1844.\n\nRicaud was elected as the candidate of the American Party to the Thirty-fourth and Thirty-fifth Congresses, serving from March 4, 1855, to March 3, 1859.  He later resumed the practice of his profession and was appointed associate judge of the second Maryland judicial district in 1864 by Governor [[Augustus Bradford]] and served during the May term.  He died in Chestertown and is interred in St. Paul's Church Cemetery.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|R000192}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=Maryland|\n  district=2 |\n  before=[[Jacob Shower]] |\n  after=[[Edwin Hanson Webster]]|\n  years=1855&ndash;1859\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ricaud, James Barroll}}\n[[Category:1808 births]]\n[[Category:1866 deaths]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Maryland Whigs]]\n[[Category:Know-Nothing members of the United States House of Representatives from Maryland]]\n[[Category:1840 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:1844 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Maryland House of Delegates]]\n[[Category:Maryland state senators]]\n[[Category:Maryland state court judges]]\n[[Category:Washington College alumni]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Maryland-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = James Barroll Ricaud\n| image       = JamesBarrollRicaud.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = James Barroll Ricaud (1859)\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1808|02|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore, Maryland]], US\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1866|01|24|1808|02|11}}\n| death_place = [[Chestertown, Maryland]], US\n| death_cause =\n| resting_place =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| residence   = \n| nationality = American\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  = Politician\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| term        =\n| predecessor =\n| successor   =\n| party       =\n| boards      =\n| religion    =\n| spouse      =\n| partner     =\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes   =\n}}\n[[File:J B Ricaud.jpg|thumb|Title page from Abstract of Infantry Tactics including exercises and maneuvers of light infantry and riflemen for the use of the militia of the United States Published by the Department of War Under the authority of an Act of Congress of the 2D of March, 1829. This first edition was signed by James B. Ricaud and given to George Vickers who would later be a US Senator from Maryland. In the private collection of H. Blair Howell]]\n'''James Barroll Ricaud''' (February 11, 1808 &ndash; January 24, 1866) was an American politician.<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=R000192 Bioguide.congress.gov]</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], Ricaud attended the common schools and graduated from [[Washington College]] of [[Chestertown, Maryland]], in 1828.  He studied law, was admitted to the bar in 1829, and commenced practice in Chestertown.  He served as a member of the [[Maryland House of Delegates]] in 1834, served in the [[Maryland State Senate]] from 1836 to 1844, and served as [[presidential elector]] on the Whig tickets in 1840 and 1844.\n\nRicaud was elected as the candidate of the American Party to the Thirty-fourth and Thirty-fifth Congresses, serving from March 4, 1855, to March 3, 1859.  He later resumed the practice of his profession and was appointed associate judge of the second Maryland judicial district in 1864 by Governor [[Augustus Bradford]] and served during the May term.  He died in Chestertown and is interred in St. Paul\u2019s Church Cemetery.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongBio|R000192}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=Maryland|\n  district=2 |\n  before=[[Jacob Shower]] |\n  after=[[Edwin Hanson Webster]]|\n  years=1855&ndash;1859\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ricaud, James Barroll}}\n[[Category:1808 births]]\n[[Category:1866 deaths]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Maryland Whigs]]\n[[Category:Know-Nothing members of the United States House of Representatives from Maryland]]\n[[Category:1840 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:1844 United States presidential electors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Maryland House of Delegates]]\n[[Category:Maryland state senators]]\n[[Category:Maryland state court judges]]\n[[Category:Washington College alumni]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Maryland-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Barroll_Ricaud"}
{"title_page": "Jealousy (2013 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Jealousy\n| image          = La Jalousie (film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| film_name      = {{Infobox name module|fr|La Jalousie}}\n| director       = [[Philippe Garrel]]\n| producer       = Sa\u00efd Ben Sa\u00efd\n| writer         = [[Marc Cholodenko]]<br>Caroline Deruas-Garrel\n| starring       = [[Louis Garrel]]<br>[[Anna Mouglalis]]\n| music          = [[Jean-Louis Aubert]]\n| cinematography = [[Willy Kurant]]\n| editing        = Yann Dedet\n| distributor    = Capricci Films\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|09|05|[[70th Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|2013|12|04|France|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 77 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \u20ac2.4 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=13979|title=La Jalouise|work=JPBox-Office|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n| gross          = $63,946<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2511670/|title=La Jalouise|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Jealousy''''' ({{lang-fr|'''La Jalousie'''}}) is a 2013 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Philippe Garrel]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.unifrance.org/movie/36211/la-jalousie|title=La Jalousie|work=[[UniFrance]]|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> starring [[Louis Garrel]] and [[Anna Mouglalis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2014/09/16/jealousy-heals-child-within/NrbvytVTTmz2w7GbfMYedJ/story.html|title='Jealousy' heals the child within|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|first=Peter|last=Keough|date=16 September 2014|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> It was screened in the main competition section at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/70th-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia70|title=Venezia 70|work=[[La Biennale]]|accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jul/25/venice-film-festival-2013-line-up/ |title=Venice film festival 2013: the full line-up|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=25 July 2013|accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref> It is the first installment in Garrel's trilogy of love, the second being ''[[In the Shadow of Women]]'' (2015) and the third being ''[[Lover for a Day]]'' (2017).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/global/cannes-mubi-philippe-garrel-lover-for-a-day-1202447485/|title=Cannes: MUBI Acquires Philippe Garrel's 'Lover for A Day' for U.S., U.K. (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=John|last=Hopewell|date=30 May 2017|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAn impoverished actor Louis tries to make his girlfriend Claudia a big star. But in spite of all his efforts he cannot get her proper roles. Eventually she falls in love with another man and cheats on him.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Louis Garrel]] as Louis \n* [[Anna Mouglalis]] as Claudia \n* Rebecca {{lang|fr|italic=no|Convenant}} as Clothilde \n* Olga Milshtein as Charlotte \n* [[Esther Garrel]] as Esther \n* Arthur Igual as the friend of Louis \n* J\u00e9r\u00f4me Huguet as Antoine \n* Manon Kneus\u00e9 as Lucie\n}}\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere in the Competition section at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]] on 5 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cineuropa.org/en/newsdetail/243079/|title=Philippe Garrel returns to the Lido with Jealousy|work=Cineuropa|first=Fabien|last=Lemercier|date=27 August 2013|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> It was released in France on 4 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/film/fichefilm_gen_cfilm=220251.html|title=La Jalousie|work=[[AlloCin\u00e9]]|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 72% based on 25 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 6.4/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jealousy_2014|title=Jealousy (2014)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 66 out of 100, based on 17 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/jealousy|title=Jealousy Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nKimber Myers of ''[[IndieWire]]'' gave the film a grade of B, writing: \"While it features characters making unrelatable decisions, this 77-minute film is nonetheless compelling and beautifully constructed, and will be of particular interest for fans of French cinema.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/08/review-philippe-garrels-jealousy-starring-louis-garrel-and-anna-mouglalis-273274/|title=Review: Philippe Garrel's 'Jealousy' Starring Louis Garrel and Anna Mouglalis|work=[[IndieWire]]|first=Kimber|last=Myers|date=22 August 2014|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> Boyd van Hoeij of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote: \"Acting is low-key but believable throughout, with Mouglalis finally shedding her supermodel looks to show the contradictory and flawed but very human character underneath.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/jealousy-la-jalousie-venice-review-620817|title=Jealousy (La Jalousie): Venice Review|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Boyd van|last=Hoeij|date=4 September 2013|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> Leslie Felperin of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"slight but watchable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/jealousy-review-venice-1200599064/|title=Venice Film Review: 'Jealousy'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Leslie|last=Felperin|date=4 September 2013|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]]'' named it the seventh best film of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/11/cahiers-du-cinemas-best-of-2013-127284/|title=Cahiers du Cinema's Best of 2013|work=[[IndieWire]]|first=Sam|last=Adams|date=26 November 2013|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2511670|Jealousy}}\n\n{{Philippe Garrel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jealousy}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2013 drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Philippe Garrel]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Jealousy\n| image          = La Jalousie (film).jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| film_name      = {{Infobox name module|fr|La Jalousie}}\n| director       = [[Philippe Garrel]]\n| producer       = Sa\u00efd Ben Sa\u00efd\n| writer         = [[Marc Cholodenko]]<br>Caroline Deruas-Garrel\n| starring       = [[Louis Garrel]]<br>[[Anna Mouglalis]]\n| music          = [[Jean-Louis Aubert]]\n| cinematography = [[Willy Kurant]]\n| editing        = Yann Dedet\n| distributor    = Capricci Films\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|09|05|[[70th Venice International Film Festival|Venice]]|2013|12|04|France|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 77 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \u20ac2.4 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/fichfilm.php?id=13979|title=La Jalouise|work=JPBox-Office|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n| gross          = $63,946<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2511670/|title=La Jalouise|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Jealousy''''' ({{lang-fr|'''La Jalousie'''}}) is a 2013 French [[drama film]] directed by [[Philippe Garrel]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.unifrance.org/movie/36211/la-jalousie|title=La Jalousie|work=[[UniFrance]]|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> starring [[Louis Garrel]] and [[Anna Mouglalis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2014/09/16/jealousy-heals-child-within/NrbvytVTTmz2w7GbfMYedJ/story.html|title='Jealousy' heals the child within|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|first=Peter|last=Keough|date=16 September 2014|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> It was screened in the main competition section at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/70th-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia70|title=Venezia 70|work=[[La Biennale]]|accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jul/25/venice-film-festival-2013-line-up/ |title=Venice film festival 2013: the full line-up|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=25 July 2013|accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref> It is the first installment in Garrel's trilogy of love, the second being ''[[In the Shadow of Women]]'' (2015) and the third being ''[[Lover for a Day]]'' (2017).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/global/cannes-mubi-philippe-garrel-lover-for-a-day-1202447485/|title=Cannes: MUBI Acquires Philippe Garrel's 'Lover for A Day' for U.S., U.K. (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=John|last=Hopewell|date=30 May 2017|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAn impoverished actor Louis tries to make his girlfriend Claudia a big star. But in spite of all his efforts he cannot get her proper roles. Eventually she falls in love with another man and cheats on him.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Louis Garrel]] as Louis \n* [[Anna Mouglalis]] as Claudia \n* Rebecca {{lang|fr|italic=no|Convenant}} as Clothilde \n* Olga Milshtein as Charlotte \n* [[Esther Garrel]] as Esther \n* Arthur Igual as the friend of Louis \n* J\u00e9r\u00f4me Huguet as Antoine \n* Manon Kneus\u00e9 as Lucie\n}}\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere in the Competition section at the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]] on 5 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cineuropa.org/en/newsdetail/243079/|title=Philippe Garrel returns to the Lido with Jealousy|work=Cineuropa|first=Fabien|last=Lemercier|date=27 August 2013|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> It was released in France on 4 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/film/fichefilm_gen_cfilm=220251.html|title=La Jalousie|work=[[AlloCin\u00e9]]|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 72% based on 25 reviews, and an [[average rating]] of 6.4/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jealousy_2014|title=Jealousy (2014)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 66 out of 100, based on 17 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/jealousy|title=Jealousy Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nKimber Myers of ''[[IndieWire]]'' gave the film a grade of B, writing: \"While it features characters making unrelatable decisions, this 77-minute film is nonetheless compelling and beautifully constructed, and will be of particular interest for fans of French cinema.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2014/08/review-philippe-garrels-jealousy-starring-louis-garrel-and-anna-mouglalis-273274/|title=Review: Philippe Garrel's 'Jealousy' Starring Louis Garrel and Anna Mouglalis|work=[[IndieWire]]|first=Kimber|last=Myers|date=22 August 2014|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> Boyd van Hoeij of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote: \"Acting is low-key but believable throughout, with Mouglalis finally shedding her supermodel looks to show the contradictory and flawed but very human character underneath.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/jealousy-la-jalousie-venice-review-620817|title=Jealousy (La Jalousie): Venice Review|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Boyd van|last=Hoeij|date=4 September 2013|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref> Leslie Felperin of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"slight but watchable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/jealousy-review-venice-1200599064/|title=Venice Film Review: 'Jealousy'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Leslie|last=Felperin|date=4 September 2013|accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]]'' named it the seventh best film of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2013/11/cahiers-du-cinemas-best-of-2013-127284/|title=Cahiers du Cinema's Best of 2013|work=[[IndieWire]]|first=Sam|last=Adams|date=26 November 2013|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2511670|Jealousy}}\n\n{{Philippe Garrel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jealousy}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2013 drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Philippe Garrel]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jealousy_(2013_film)"}
{"title_page": "2019\u201320 Czech First Division (women)", "text_new": "{{infobox football league season\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| competition        = [[Czech First Division (women)]]\n| season             = 2019\u201320\n| winners            = [[SK Slavia Prague (women)|Slavia Praha]]\n| promoted           = -\n| relegated          = -\n| continentalcup1    = [[2020\u201321 UEFA Women's Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = Slavia Praha, [[AC Sparta Prague (women)|Sparta Prague]]\n| matches            = 52\n| total goals        = 249\n| league topscorer   = [[Kate\u0159ina Svitkov\u00e1]] (23)\n| biggest home win   = {{nobreak|Slavia Praha 13\u20130 Dukla Praha}}\n| biggest away win   = {{nobreak|Dukla Praha 0\u201311 Sparta Prague}}\n| highest scoring    = {{nobreak|Slavia Praha 13\u20131 Pardubice}}\n| longest wins       = 13 matches <br />{{nobreak|Slavia Praha}}\n| longest unbeaten   = 13 matches <br />{{nobreak|Slavia Praha}}\n| longest winless    = 7 matches <br />{{nobreak|Liberec}}\n| longest losses     = 4 matches <br />{{nobreak|Pardubice}}, {{nobreak|Liberec}}\n| highest attendance = 350 <br />{{nobreak|Slavia Praha 3\u20132 Sparta Prague}}\n| lowest attendance  = 30 <br />{{nobreak|Plze\u0148 6\u20131 Dukla Praha}}\n| average attendance = \n| prevseason = [[2018\u201319 Czech First Division (women)|2018\u201319]]\n| nextseason = ''2020\u201321''\n| updated    = 22 March 2020\n}}\nThe '''2019\u201320 [[Czech First Division (women)]]''' is the 27th season of the [[Czech Republic]]'s top-tier [[Association football|football]] league for women. [[AC Sparta Prague (women)|Sparta Prague]] were the defending champions.\n\nOn 7 April 2020, the [[Football Association of the Czech Republic]]'s board of directors agreed to cancel the season early during the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://facr.fotbal.cz/vv-facr-ukoncil-amaterske-souteze-pohar-se-odklada/a12281|title=VV FA\u010cR ukon\u010dil amat\u00e9rsk\u00e9 sout\u011b\u017ee, poh\u00e1r se odkl\u00e1d\u00e1|publisher=fotbal.cz|date=2020-04-07|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nThe eight teams will play each other twice for a total of 14 matches per team. After that the top four teams will play a championship round for another six matches per team. The bottom placed four teams play the relegation round. The champion and runners-up qualify for the [[2020\u201321 UEFA Women's Champions League]].\n\n==Teams==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Team\n! Home town\n! Home ground\n! Capacity\n|-\n| [[FK Pardubice (women)|Pardubice]] || [[Pardubice]] || [[Letn\u00ed stadion (Pardubice)|Letn\u00ed Stadion]] || 1,000\n|- \n| [[FK Dukla Praha (women)|Dukla Praha]] || [[Prague]] || [[Stadion SK Prosek|SK Prosek]] || \n|-\n| [[Lokomotiva Brno Horn\u00ed Her\u0161pice (women)|Lokomotiva Brno H. H.]] || [[Brno]]|| Horn\u00ed Her\u0161pice || \n|-\n| [[SK Slavia Praha (women)|Slavia Praha]] || [[Prague]]|| [[Na Chvalech|Stadion SC Xaverov]] || 3,400\n|- \n| [[FC Slovan Liberec (women)|Slovan Liberec]] || [[Liberec]] || Fr\u00fddlant v \u010cech\u00e1ch || \n|- \n| [[1. FC Slov\u00e1cko (women)|Slov\u00e1cko]] || [[Uhersk\u00e9 Hradi\u0161t\u011b]] || [[M\u011bstsk\u00fd fotbalov\u00fd stadion Miroslava Valenty|M\u011bstsk\u00fd stadion]] || 8,121 \n|-\n| [[AC Sparta Prague (women)|Sparta Prague]] || [[Prague]]|| [[Strahov Stadium]] || 20,000\n|- \n| [[FC Viktoria Plze\u0148 (women)|Viktoria Plze\u0148]] || [[Plze\u0148]] || SK Sm\u00edchov Plze\u0148 || \n|}\n\n===Stadia and locations===\n{{location map+ |Czech Republic |width=475 |float=none |caption=Location of teams in '''2019\u201320 Czech First Division (women)''' |places=\n{{location map~ |Czech Republic |lat=50.083333 |long=14.416667 |label=[[FK Dukla Praha (women)|Dukla]]<br />[[SK Slavia Praha (women)|Slavia]]<br>[[AC Sparta Prague (women)|Sparta]]}}\n{{location map~ |Czech Republic |lat=49.227162 |long=16.586276 |label=[[Lokomotiva Brno Horn\u00ed Her\u0161pice (women)|Brno H. H.]]}}\n{{location map~ |Czech Republic |lat=50.040958 |long=15.77125 |label=[[FK Pardubice (women)|Pardubice]]}}\n{{location map~ |Czech Republic |lat=50.716667 |long=15.066667 |label=[[FC Slovan Liberec (women)|Liberec]] |position=left}}\n{{location map~ |Czech Republic |lat=49.05947  |long=17.44629  |label=[[1. FC Slov\u00e1cko (women)|Slov\u00e1cko]]}}\n{{location map~ |Czech Republic |lat=49.7475   |long=13.3775   |label=[[FC Viktoria Plze\u0148 (women)|Plze\u0148]] |position=left}}\n}}\n\n==Regular season==\n\n===Standings===\nThe regular season ended on 7 April 2020.\n\n{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=football\n|update=22 March 2020\n|source=[https://int.women.soccerway.com/national/czech-republic/1-liga/20192020/regular-season/r54532/ Soccerway]\n|show_matches=false\n\n<!--Update team positions here-->\n|team1=SLA |team2=SPA |team3=VIK |team4=SVK |team5=LOK |team6=DUK |team7=SLO |team8=PAR\n\n<!--Update team qualifications here (defined below)-->\n|result1=CH |result2=CH |result3=CH |result4=CH |result5=REL |result6=REL |result7=REL |result8=REL\n\n<!--Update team results here and then (if needed positions above). Dont forget to update the date above (update parameter)-->\n|win_LOK=3 |draw_LOK=2 |loss_LOK=8 |gf_LOK=16 |ga_LOK=36 |status_LOK= <!-- Lokomotiva Brno Horn\u00ed Her\u0161pice -->\n|win_DUK=3 |draw_DUK=2 |loss_DUK=8 |gf_DUK=13 |ga_DUK=57 |status_DUK= <!-- Dukla Praha -->\n|win_PAR=3 |draw_PAR= |loss_PAR=10 |gf_PAR=12 |ga_PAR=56 |status_PAR= <!-- Pardubice -->\n|win_SLA=13 |draw_SLA= |loss_SLA= |gf_SLA=86 |ga_SLA=7 |status_SLA=C,Q <!-- Slavia Praha -->\n|win_SLO=2 |draw_SLO=3 |loss_SLO=8 |gf_SLO=7 |ga_SLO=30 |status_SLO= <!-- Slovan Liberec -->\n|win_SVK=4 |draw_SVK=3 |loss_SVK=6 |gf_SVK=15 |ga_SVK=26 |status_SVK= <!-- Slov\u00e1cko -->\n|win_SPA=11 |draw_SPA= |loss_SPA=2 |gf_SPA=71 |ga_SPA=9 |status_SPA=Q <!-- Sparta Praha -->\n|win_VIK=8 |draw_VIK= |loss_VIK=5 |gf_VIK=29